abstract = {Remote sensing products, such as the fraction of reflected solar radiation$\backslash$nflux, as well$\backslash$n$\backslash$nas the amount of radiation absorbed in the photosynthetically active$\backslash$nspectral region and$\backslash$n$\backslash$nthe Leaf Area Index (LAI), are operationally available from Space$\backslash$nAgencies. Climate$\backslash$n$\backslash$nmodels may benefit from these products provided their one dimensional$\backslash$n(1-D) radiation$\backslash$n$\backslash$ntransfer schemes effectively represent the three dimensional (3-D)$\backslash$neffects implied by$\backslash$n$\backslash$nthe internal spatial variability of vegetation canopies, e.g., the$\backslash$nleaf area density, at all$\backslash$n$\backslash$nscales and resolutions involved (say from 1 to 100 kilometers). Failing$\backslash$nto do so leads to$\backslash$n$\backslash$ninherent inconsistencies between the domain-averaged reflected and$\backslash$nabsorbed fluxes,$\backslash$n$\backslash$nand the implied Leaf Area Index. We propose a comprehensive approach$\backslash$nwhich introduces$\backslash$n$\backslash$na parameterization of the internal variability of the LAI in the 1-D$\backslash$nrepresentation of the$\backslash$n$\backslash$nradiation scheme, called a domain-averaged structure factor, and provides$\backslash$na description$\backslash$n$\backslash$nof the radiant fluxes fully consistent with the LAI specified by remote$\backslash$nsensing. We$\backslash$n$\backslash$ntake this opportunity to revisit and update the two-stream formulations$\backslash$nimplemented in$\backslash$n$\backslash$nclimate models to accurately estimate the fractions of radiation absorbed$\backslash$nseparately by the$\backslash$n$\backslash$nvegetation canopy and the underlying surface. This is achieved by$\backslash$nisolating the$\backslash$n$\backslash$ncontributions of the vegetation canopy alone, the background as seen$\backslash$nthrough the canopy$\backslash$n$\backslash$